mkring 1319","before 1319":"før 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1349":"omkring 1349","1453":"1453","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Sandiacre, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sandiacre, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1280–about 1349":"circa 1280–circa 1349","1284–1341":"1284–1341","1319–1362":"1319–1362","1280–1349":"1280–1349","about 1280":"circa 1280","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1284":"1284","Abt 1319":"circa 1319","before 1319":"vóór 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1349":"circa 1349","1453":"1453","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Sandiacre, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sandiacre, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1280–about 1349":"about 1280–about 1349","1284–1341":"1284–1341","1319–1362":"1319–1362","1280–1349":"1280–1349","about 1280":"about 1280","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1284":"1284","Abt 1319":"about 1319","before 1319":"before 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1349":"about 1349","1453":"1453","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Sandiacre, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sandiacre, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hillary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran.","English (of Norman origin):","from the Middle English and Old French male or female personal name <i>Hilari(e)</i>, <i>Ilari(e)</i>, and <i>Elari(e)</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> and <i>Hilaria</i> ‘joyful’ (from Greek <i>hilaros</i>). The Latin name was chosen by many early Christians to express their joy and hope of salvation, and was borne by several saints, including a 4th-century bishop of Poitiers (died 368) noted for his vigorous resistance to the Arian heresy, and a 5th-century bishop of Arles. Largely due to veneration of Saint Hilarius of Poitiers, the name became popular in France in the forms <i>Hilari</i> and <i>Hilaire</i>, and was brought to England by the Norman conquerors. Although quite popular in France, it was only occasionally used in England, where it was confused with the name in 2 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellery","meanings":["variant of   Hillary  .","habitational name from Elleray in Windermere (Westmorland), probably from Old Norse <i>elri</i> ‘alder’ + <i>vrá</i> ‘nook’.","English:"]},{"name":"Gloor","meanings":["Swiss German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillier","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Surrey): occupational name for a roofer from Middle English <i>hil(l)ier</i>, <i>hul(li)er</i>, <i>hel(li)er</i> ‘roofer, slater, tiler’, agent nouns from the Middle English verb <i>hil(i)en</i>, <i>hel(i)an</i>, <i>hul(i)en</i> ‘to put a roof on; cover with a roof’.","French: from the personal name <i>Hillier</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Alario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Orazio, Carlo, Rocco, Salvatore, Vita, Vitina.","Italian: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Ilario</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  ).","Italian (Sicily): probably a status name from dialect <i>alariu</i> ‘herald’."]},{"name":"Glor","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillery","meanings":["English: variant of   Hillary  . This name has long been established in Ireland (Clare)."]},{"name":"Hilaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Pierre, Antoine, Chantal, Edeline, Georges, Luc, Maryse, Mimose, Serge, Yolaine.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Hilaire</i>, French form of   Hillary   1. This surname is most common in Haiti. Compare   Helaire  ."]},{"name":"Hilleary","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Hillary  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Allaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Lucien, Alphonse, Antoine, Armand, Emile, Michel, Pierre, Raoul, Raymonde, Rolande.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Allaire</i>, a variant of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  ). Compare   Dallaire  .","History: Jean and Charles Allaire, two brothers from the Poitou region of France, are recorded in Quebec City, QC, in 1662 and 1663, respectively, the years of their marriage. The descendants of one or another brother also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Dallaire</i>, <i>Delair</i>, and <i>Delaire</i>. — Alexandre Allaire, a Huguenot refugee, brought the name from La Rochelle in France to New Rochelle, NY, in 1686, via the West Indies. He is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Hilario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Julio, Alfredo, Luis, Abelardo, Arturo, Eduardo, Francisco, Juan, Mario, Pedro, Carlos, Cesar.  Portuguese Afonso, Joao.","Portuguese (<b>Hilário</b>) and Spanish: from a personal name ofthe same origin as   Hillary   1."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":57,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry Hillary was born about 1280, in Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England. He married Joane II De Marmion before 1319. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1349, at the age of 71."},"et":{"about 1280–about 1349":"umbes 1280–umbes 1349","1284–1341":"1284–1341","1319–1362":"1319–1362","1280–1349":"1280–1349","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1284":"1284","Abt 1319":"umbes 1319","before 1319":"enne 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1453":"1453","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"